widgets_values: Using the model that you generated the original animation with makes a **huge** difference. Probably the biggest in terms of impacting adherence to your original video.

After the SD1.5 checkpoint, this is probably the biggest for input video adherence.

I recommend you check out this website for finding a good model fro your use-case: https://openmodeldb.info/

For AI animations: https://openmodeldb.info/models/4x-LexicaDAT2-otf

For anime: https://openmodeldb.info/models/4x-IllustrationJaNai-V1-DAT2

For realistic: https://openmodeldb.info/models/4x-RealisticRescaler

I mostly applied the logic here from my other workflows and it seems to work nicely!

I didn't play too much with the weight_types but think the and the start/end steps/strength could be worth playing with but I have a feeling it's not going to have a major impact.
I haven't really played around with this much tbh - if it ain't broken...

I haven't played around too much with a lot of the settings here.

Denoise is probably the most significant - naturally, the higer you set it the more stuff it generated. Anything above 0.6 tends to cause weird issues, below 0.2 tends to not fix stuff. 0.4 is best in my experience - especailly with the tiling stuff applied.

If you want it to run faster, turning down the scale will help but will result in less detail being generated.
